ce:section.ce:para:
As previously reported [14], interfering metal ions, such as Pb2+, Mn2+, Sn4+, Co2+, Ni2+, Nd3+, Cr3+, Cu2+, Hg2+, Fe3+ and Fe2+, with concentrations of 300 μM were selected to assess the selectivity of CDs-NH2 for metal ions. The mixed solution was placed at room temperature for 10 min to ensure the equilibrium of the mixed solution system and then the fluorescence spectra were obtained. In case of ferrous ion detection, to prevent the oxidation reaction of ferrous ions, ready-to-use ferrous ions samples were used and the proper amount (1 mol%) of sodium sulfite as reducing agent to prevent Fe2+ conversion into Fe3+ during the detection process. PL spectrum was performed and calculated the sensitivity for detection of Fe2+ according to the reference [

                           14

                        ]. In brief, 4 mg CDs-NH2 was dissolved in 10 ml deionized water, and different concentrations of Fe2+ were added into the aqueous solution of CDs-NH2. The fluorescence intensity was recorded after 10 min equilibrium. The quenching area increased with the increase of Fe2+ concentration. The quantitative equation was established according to the relationship between the attenuation percentage of fluorescence integration area and the concentration of ferrous ions.
